Blocks.childText: PENITENTIAL EXERCISES. 342 C. M. 1 I ASK the gift of righteousness, The sin-subduing power, Power to believe, and go in peace, And never grieve thee more. 2 I ask the blood-bought pardon sealed, The liberty from sin, The grace infused, the love revealed, The kingdom fixed within. 3 Thou hear'st me for salvation pray ; Thou seest my heart's desire ; Made ready in thy powerful day, Thy fullness I require. 4 My vehement soul cries out, oppressed, Impatient to be freed! Nor can I, Lord, nor will I rest, Till I am saved indeed. 5 Art thou not able to convert? Art thou not willing too ? To change this old rebellious heart, To conquer and renew ? 6 Thou canst, thou wilt, I dare believe, So arm me with thy power, That I to sin may never cleave, May never feel it more. Charles Wesley. 343 C. M. 1 How sad our state by nature is ! Our sin how deep it stains! And Satan binds our captive souls Fast in his slavish chains. 16 241
